The CHSH inequality can also be thought of as a &quot;game&quot; in which Alice and Bob try to coordinate their actions. Victor prepares two bits, formula_39 and formula_40, independently and at random. He sends bit formula_39 to Alice and bit formula_40 to Bob. Alice and Bob win if they return answer bits formula_43 and formula_44 to Victor, satisfying
formula_45
Or, equivalently, Alice and Bob win if the logical AND of formula_39 and formula_40 is the logical XOR of formula_43 and formula_44. Alice and Bob can agree upon any strategy they desire before the game, but they cannot communicate once the game begins. In any theory based on local hidden variables, Alice and Bob&#x27;s probability of winning is no greater than formula_50, regardless of what strategy they agree upon beforehand. However, if they share an entangled quantum state, their probability of winning can be as large asformula_51

==Variations and related results==
===Bell (1964)===
Bell&#x27;s 1964 paper shows that a very simple local hidden-variable model can in restricted circumstances reproduce the predictions of quantum mechanics, but then he demonstrates that, in general, such models give different predictions. Bell considers a refinement by David Bohm of the Einstein–Podolsky–Rosen (EPR) thought experiment. In this scenario, a pair of particles are formed together in such a way that they are described by a spin singlet state (which is an example of an entangled state). The particles then move apart in opposite directions. Each particle is measured by a Stern–Gerlach device, a measuring instrument that can be oriented in different directions and that reports one of two possible outcomes, representable by formula_6 and formula_7. The configuration of each measuring instrument is represented by a unit vector, and the quantum-mechanical prediction for the correlation between two detectors with settings formula_54 and formula_55 is
formula_56
In particular, if the orientation of the two detectors is the same (formula_57), then the outcome of one measurement is certain to be the negative of the outcome of the other, giving formula_58. And if the orientations of the two detectors are orthogonal (formula_59), then the outcomes are uncorrelated, and formula_60. Bell proves by example that these special cases &quot;can&quot; be explained in terms of hidden variables, then proceeds to show that the full range of possibilities involving intermediate angles &quot;cannot&quot;.

Bell posited that a local hidden-variable model for these correlations would explain them in terms of an integral over the possible values of some hidden parameter formula_61:formula_62
where formula_63 is a probability density function. The two functions formula_64 and formula_65 provide the responses of the two detectors given the orientation vectors and the hidden variable:formula_66
Crucially, the outcome of detector formula_67 does not depend upon formula_55, and likewise the outcome of formula_69 does not depend upon formula_54, because the two detectors are physically separated. Now we suppose that the experimenter has a &quot;choice&quot; of settings for the second detector: it can be set either to formula_55 or to formula_72. Bell proves that the difference in correlation between these two choices of detector setting must satisfy the inequalityformula_73
However, it is easy to find situations where quantum mechanics violates the Bell inequality. For example, let the vectors formula_54 and formula_55 be orthogonal, and let formula_72 lie in their plane at a 45° angle from both of them. Thenformula_77
